subSection.paragraph:
Microbial transformation is a biological synthesis process that uses enzymes inside microorganism as biocatalysts. The principal advantages are the environmental safety, mild conditions, and characteristic regio- and stereoselectivities of these biocatalytic processes (
Ahmad et al., 2017
). Thus, this technique permits access to remote positions on molecules and offers a useful alternative to chemical approaches (
Parshikov et al., 2006
).

Excessive and persistent production of cytokines and chemokines are involved in the pathogenesis of infections, allergies, and immune related diseases, such as autoimmune diseases, coronary artery disease, obesity, cancers, and neurodegenerative diseases (
Borish and Steinke, 2003
; 
Moilanen, 2014
; 
Perretti et al., 2015
; 
Shachar and Karin, 2013
). Cytokines, a class of small cell-signaling proteins, are key modulators of inflammation participating in acute and chronic inflammation (
Aggarwal et al., 2006
; 
Dinarello, 2000
; 
Shachar and Karin, 2013
; 
Zhang and An, 2007
). Interleukin (IL)-1, tumor necrosis factor (TNF), interferon (IFN)-γ, IL-12, IL-18 and granulocyte-macrophage colony stimulating factor (GM-CSF) are pro-inflammatory cytokines that promote inflammation (
Zhang and An, 2007
). Chemokines, structurally related chemotactic cytokines, are a specific subclass of cytokines. Chemokines are categorized into four groups: 
C
– 
C
chemokines (monocyte chemoattractant protein (MCP-1), monocyte inflammatory protein (MIP)-1α, MIP-1β, and RANTES), C-X-C chemokines (IL-8 also called growth related oncogene or GRO/KC), 
C
chemokines (lymphotactin), and CX 
3
C
chemokines (
Charo and Ransohoff, 2006
; 
Rollins, 1997
; 
Zhang and An, 2007
). They are produced during infections, or as a response to inflammatory stimuli, and facilitate immune response by targeting cells of the innate and adaptive immune system (
Griffith et al., 2014
). Therefore, cytokines and chemokines play a pivotal role in the development, homeostasis, activation, differentiation, regulation, and functions of innate and adaptive immunity (
Ramesh et al., 2013
). Glucocorticoids (GCs), such as dexamethasone, have been known to suppress a plethora of pro-inflammatory genes encoding cytokines, chemokines, cell adhesion molecules, and other mediators, thereby interfering with the inflammatory response (
Barnes, 2006
, 
2011
; 
Brattsand and Linden, 1996
; 
Tuckermann et al., 2005
). GCs have been used as therapeutic treatment in a wide range of autoimmune and inflammatory diseases (
Barnes, 2006
; 
Tuckermann et al., 2005
). However, long-term systemic treatment of GCs remain as the cause of unsolved problems, such as the GC resistance or undesired side effects (
Barnes, 2011
; 
Dejager et al., 2014
). Inhibition of cytokines release can be an alternative therapeutic strategy for alleviating a variety of disorders (
Shin et al., 2010
). Thus, agents that modulate cytokine-mediated inflammatory pathways may be considered as an effective therapeutic strategy for preventing inflammatory reactions and diseases (
Dinarello, 2010
; 
Gupta et al., 2014
).

A
great number of naturally occurring 
ent
-kaurane diterpenoids have been isolated from many plant families (
García et al., 2007
). They have also attracted interest because of their structures and wide range of biological activities (
Ding et al., 2017
; 
Hanson, 2009
). According to the literature, tetracyclic diterpenoids possess rigid ring systems, and they have received special attention as substrates for microbial transformation to produce sizable amounts of new compounds otherwise difficult or impossible to synthesize by chemical methods (
Hanson, 1992
; 
Takahashi et al., 2014
). Thus, the aim of this study was the microbial transformation of 
2
to obtain diverse compounds and characterize their new biological activities. Because tetracyclic diterpenoids possess steroid-like skeletons (
Hanson, 1992
) and they are capable of inhibiting proinflammatory cytokines (
Boonkaewwan et al., 2006
; Hueso-Falc´on et al., 2011; 
Kim et al., 2017
), the effects of all isolates on LPS-induced cytokine production by THP-1 cells were examined, with dexamethasone used as a positive control. Herein, we describe the production, isolation, and structural characterization of isolates as well as their effects on cytokine production. In addition, interactions of biotransformation products with the active site of the glucocorticoid receptor (GR) were also analyzed through molecular docking.

THP-1 cell lysates were prepared using a lysis buffer containing 0.1% Triton X-100 and proteinase inhibitors (Roche, Nutley, NJ, 
USA
). Protein concentrations were determined using the Bradford method (DC Protein Assay Reagent, Bio-Rad, Hercules, CA, 
USA
). Western blotting was performed as described. In brief, after membrane blocking, a primary rabbit antibody against caspase-3 (#9662, Cell Signaling Technology, Danvers, MA, 
USA
), MyD88 (GTX112987, GeneTex Biotech, Irvine, CA, 
USA
), or TLR4 (GTX125909, GeneTex Biotech) was incubated at 4 
◦
C
at a 1:1000 ratio overnight. β- Actin (1:2000, GTX109639, GeneTex Biotech) was used as a loading control. Membranes were then washed with TBST and incubated with horseradish peroxidase (HRP)- conjugated anti-rabbit secondary antibody (1:2000, Thermo Fisher Scientific, Rockford, IL, 
USA
) at room temperature for 1 h. Proteins were detected by enhanced chemiluminescence (ECL) (Amersham Biosciences, Piscataway, NJ, 
USA
) and then visualized with the UVP autochemi™ bioimaging system (Analytik jena, Upland, CA, 
USA
).
